COVID-19 Analysis in the US

2024-11-20

Introduction

The COVID-19 pandemic has had a profound impact on healthcare, economies, and daily life worldwide. The purpose of this analysis is to explore the COVID-19 case and death trends in the United States using the dataset provided by Johns Hopkins University. Specifically, we aim to answer the following question:

What are the trends in confirmed COVID-19 cases and deaths over time in the United States, and how do they differ across states?

Data Source

The data is sourced from the Johns Hopkins University GitHub repository, which hosts daily updates on COVID-19 statistics. We will specifically use the following datasets:

  • data/time_series_covid19_deaths_US.csv: Contains the number of deaths from COVID-19 in the United States.
  • data/time_series_covid19_confirmed_US.csv: Contains the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the United States.

Data Import and Tidying

Discussion of Initial Processing

We observe that the original data is structured as a list of time-series of data points per locality. In order perform the desired analysis, we need to pivot the time-series columns to get a list of data points.

# Aggregate by state and date
deaths_statewise <- deaths_data_tidy %>%
  group_by(Province_State, date) %>%
  summarise(total_deaths = sum(deaths, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Province_State'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.
deaths_statewise = data.frame(deaths_statewise)
head(deaths_statewise)
##   Province_State       date total_deaths
## 1        Alabama 2020-01-22            0
## 2        Alabama 2020-01-23            0
## 3        Alabama 2020-01-24            0
## 4        Alabama 2020-01-25            0
## 5        Alabama 2020-01-26            0
## 6        Alabama 2020-01-27            0
# Plotting confirmed cases over time for each state
ggplot(deaths_statewise, aes(x = as.Date(date), y = total_deaths, color = Province_State)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Deaths Over Time by State",
       x = "Date",
       y = "Total Deaths") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "right")  # Position the legend on the right

Discussion of Death Counts

We plot the death counts over time by state. We see a similarly-shaped curve per state. The shape of the curve may be influenced by the lockdown measures implemented during the time period.

# Aggregate by state and date
confirmed_statewise <- confirmed_data_tidy %>%
  group_by(Province_State, date) %>%
  summarise(total_confirmed = sum(confirmed, na.rm = TRUE))

## the `.groups` argument.
confirmed_statewise = data.frame(confirmed_statewise)

Discussion of Confirmed Cases

We plot the cases counts over time by state. We see a similarly-shaped curve per state. We observe for both functions that they are non-decreasing over time. We assume that these are cumulative totals reported at a given time for this data. We observe the scale of deaths is up to 100,000 whereas the scale of cases is 12,500,000.

Data Visualization

Perform required pre-processing for visualizations.

merged_data <- deaths_statewise %>%
  inner_join(confirmed_statewise, by = c("Province_State", "date"))

merged_data$date <- as.Date(merged_data$date)

merged_data_clean <- merged_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(date) & !is.na(total_confirmed) & !is.na(total_deaths) &
         !is.infinite(total_confirmed) & !is.infinite(total_deaths))

Visualization 2: Confirmed Cases by State (Latest Date)

# Plotting confirmed cases for all states on the latest date
latest_date <- max(confirmed_statewise$date)
latest_confirmed <- confirmed_statewise %>%
  filter(date == latest_date)

ggplot(latest_confirmed, aes(x = reorder(Province_State, -total_confirmed), y = total_confirmed)) +
  geom_col(fill = "skyblue") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = paste("Confirmed COVID-19 Cases by State on", latest_date),
       x = "State",
       y = "Total Confirmed Cases") +
  theme_minimal()

Discussion of Bar Chart of Cases by State.

We plot cases vs.state and see that densely populated states like New York, Florida and California have significantly high number of cases.

Model: Regression Analysis of Confirmed Cases Over Time

We will model the number of confirmed cases over time in California to understand the trend better.

# Fit a linear model
model <- lm(total_confirmed ~ date, data = filter(merged_data, Province_State == "California"))

# Summarizing the model
summary(model)

  labs(title = "Linear Model of COVID-19 Confirmed Cases in California",
       x = "Date",
       y = "Total Confirmed Cases") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Discussion of Model

We see that modeling confirmed cases linearly over date achieved R squared of 0.96 which is fairly good. However, information about lockdown measures could help explain the deviation from the linear trend.

Discussion of Sources of Bias

The COVID-19 data is subject to several biases:

  1. Reporting Bias: Different states may have varying criteria for testing and reporting cases, leading to inconsistencies in reported numbers.

  2. Data Completeness: The dataset may be incomplete for earlier dates as testing was not widespread or uniformly applied.

  3. Population Size: States with larger populations will inevitably show higher case numbers, which should be accounted for when comparing states.

  4. Temporal Bias: The timing of interventions (e.g., lockdowns) greatly influences case counts and could provide skewed results if not properly analyzed.

Conclusion

This analysis explored the trends of COVID-19 confirmed cases and deaths in the United States, focusing on California. The visualizations demonstrated the exponential growth of cases, while linear modeling provided insights into trends over time. However, biases in reporting and data completeness must be considered when interpreting the results.
